Investigating Fordgobike trips¶

by Hammam Al-Alfi¶

Investigation Overview¶

This slides investigate the duration of the individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area on 2018.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains informations about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area on 2018.
The informations includes:

  • The starting and ending station of the trip and thier coordinates.
  • The duration of the trip .
  • The date and time of the start and end of the trip.
  • The user type (Customer or Subsecriber).
  • If the member is enrolled in Bike Share For All program (Yes or No).
  • A derived-distance-column that gives the shortest distance on the surface of an ellipsoidal model of the earth between the start and end station.

The distribution of the trips duration¶

I am going to start my presentantion by showing the distribution of the trips that has done on 2018.

  • The subplot on the left showing the distibution of the duration using logarithmic scale for the duration as minutes,linear scale for the frequency and a vertical line showing the mean of the duration of all trips over 2018.From this subplot we see that there are no trips with durations less than one minute and the majority of distribution falls under short durations.

  • The subplot on the right showing the distibution of the duration using logarithmic scale for the frequency and linear scale for the duration as hours.From this subplot we see that we have got no duration longer than 24 hours.

The distribution of the distancs between the start and end stations.¶

The two subplots below showing the distribution of the distances as follows:

  • the one on the left showing the distribution using square root scale for the distances that there is a spike on the distribution around the zero and this is because there is an amount of trips that started and ended at the same station so they have a distance of zero and because some stations are in quite close proximity. Further more, there is a gap between the spike and the rest of the distribution, this is because there is a few amount of stations with close proximity and then there is a gap in the distances between the stations.The rest of the distribution gose some how normally distibuted.

  • The one on right has used logarithmic scale for the frequency and square root scale for the distances.From this plot we can see the outliers with one trip with a distance between 36 and 49 miles.

Distance Vs Duration.¶

This plot is a heat map of the distance as miles on square root scale on the y axis and the duration as minutes on log scale on the x axis and the color bar showing the count of the trips for each area.

  • This plot shows the gap in the distance distribution

  • look how the majority (purple area) of the trips follow a positive relation for short durations (above the gap) on a log-square scale.

  • For quite short and zero distances (under the gap) the trips durations are of wide range from 1 minute to over 1000 minutes.

  • For large (longer than the purple area) the distance tends to fall between a specific range except some outliers like the one between 36 and 49 miles.

  • The plot showing that the longer the duration of the trip the more likely to be done by a Customer .
In [33]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14.70,8.27))
# getting a log scaled bins of the duration as minutes
bin_edges = 10**np.linspace(np.log10(df.duration_minutes).min(),np.log10(df.duration_minutes).max(),50)
# getting the number of points in each bin
bin_idxs = pd.cut(df.duration_minutes,bin_edges,include_lowest =True,right=True,labels=False).astype(int)
pts_per_bin = df.groupby(bin_idxs).size()
#plotting a weighted histogram of the duration as minutes and Subscriber user type
plt.hist(df.duration_minutes,
         bins = bin_edges,
         weights = (df.user_type=='Subscriber')/pts_per_bin[bin_idxs].values,
         edgecolor='black',
         label='Subscriber')
#plotting a weighted histogram of the duration as minutes and Customer user type
plt.hist(df.duration_minutes,
         bins = bin_edges,
         weights = (df.user_type=='Customer')/pts_per_bin[bin_idxs].values,
         edgecolor='black',
         label='Customer',
        alpha=0.5)
#polishing the plot by setting the title of the legend,relabeling the ticks and setting the labels.
plt.legend(title='User Type',loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5),
            title_fontsize = 12)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([1,10,100,1000],[1,10,100,1000])
plt.yticks([0,0.5,1],['0%','50%','100%'])
plt.xlabel('Duration[minutes]'.title(),
               fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
plt.ylabel('Percentage'.title(),
               fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
plt.title('User type Vs Duration'.title(),
               fontsize = 14, weight = "bold");

User type , Bike Share For All program and Duration.¶

This last plot is a heat map comparing the average of duration with respect to the user type and if the member is enrolled in Bike Share For All program.

  • Here we see that there are no Customers enrolled in the program
  • On average the Subscribers that are enrolled in the program tends to do tips with duration of 2 minutes longer than the ones that are not enrolled.
  • The Customers that are not enrolled in the program on average do trips with longer duration than the others.
In [37]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14.70,8.27))
#getting the grouped means with respect to both bike_share_for_all_trip and user_type and then resetting the index
group_mean = df.groupby(['bike_share_for_all_trip', 'user_type']).duration_minutes.mean()
group_mean = group_mean.reset_index()
#reshape the group_mean to use it in heatmap plot
group_mean = group_mean.pivot(index = 'bike_share_for_all_trip', columns = 'user_type',
                            values = 'duration_minutes')
#plotting a heat map and use annotations.
sns.heatmap(group_mean, annot = True,cmap='Blues',cbar_kws={'label': 'Mean Duratn [minutes]'})
plt.xlabel('User Type'.title(),
               fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
plt.ylabel('Enrolled in Bike Share For All program'.title(),
               fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
plt.title('User type , Bike Share For All program and Duration.'.title(),
               fontsize = 14, weight = "bold");
